---
title: Curried Shrimp & Chickpea Lettuce Wraps with Sweet Potato, Peas & Red Pepper Cilantro Sauce
description: If you’ve been on the request line for light, tasty, satisfying and vegan dinner ideas, this one’s going out to you. First you’ll smash chickpeas (to create jagged edges for browning) and roast with sweet potato, cumin, and curry until crispy, then add to sauteed peas, onion, garlic, ginger, with a bright squeeze of lemon. Stuff all that warm goodness into crisp, cool lettuce leaves, drizzle with a tangy red pepper-cilantro sauce and it’s vegan wrap music for your taste buds.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/643edf7d9d83e260f8084984-f9ca31ea.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/6489ec26f60ba0cad8796992.pdf
nutrition:
  calories: 740 kcal
  fat: 17 g
  saturated fat: 1.5 g
  carbohydrates: 103 g
  sugar: 36 g
  protein: 35 g
  fiber: 16 g
  sodium: 1730 mg
cuisine: Indian
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/curried-shrimp-and-chickpea-lettuce-wraps-6489ec26f60ba0cad8796992
course: main course
time required: 35 minutes
---

Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @sweet potato{1} into ¼-inch pieces.

Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%400g can}; thoroughly pat dry with #paper towels{}. On a clean flat work surface, place chickpeas between 2 large pieces of #plastic wrap{}. Smash with a #mallet{} or the bottom of a #pan{} until broken apart (chickpeas should not be completely mashed).

In a #large bowl{}, combine sweet potato, smashed chickpeas, half the @cumin{1%tsp} (all for 4 servings), @curry powder{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4), a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}; toss until evenly coated. Spread out on a #baking sheet{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}. (For 4, divide everything between 2 sheets; roast on top and middle racks, swapping positions halfway through.)

While veggies roast, halve, peel, and finely dice @yellow onion{1}. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}. Halve @lemon{1}. Roughly chop @cilantro{¼%ounce}. Trim and discard root end from @baby lettuce{1}; separate leaves.

Rinse @shrimp{10%oz} under cold water. Pat shrimp dry with paper towels; season with salt and pepper. Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add shrimp in a single layer; cook, stirring occasionally, until cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add onion and a pinch of salt; cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly browned and softened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Reduce heat to medium and add @peas{4%oz}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{2-4%minutes} more.

Add garlic and ginger to pan; cook, stirring constantly, until fragrant, ~{1-3%minutes}.

Use pan used for shrimp here. Stir in remaining @curry powder{1%tbsp}, @water{½%cup} (1 cup for 4 servings), @salt{¼%tsp} (½ tsp for 4), and juice from half the lemon. Cook, stirring occasionally, until water has mostly evaporated, ~{2-4%minutes} more.

Stir roasted chickpea mixture into pan. Taste and season filling with salt and pepper if desired.

Stir shrimp into chickpea mixture.

In a #medium microwave-safe bowl{}, combine @red pepper jam{2%units}, cilantro, @water{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings), and juice from remaining lemon. Cover tightly with plastic wrap and #microwave{} until warmed through, ~{20-30%seconds}.

Divide lettuce leaves between plates (pat dry if needed). Fill leaves with chickpea filling. Drizzle with as much sauce as you like and serve.